On this day in 1966 four Caterpillar tractors began dragging the 1,300-ton S.S. Klondike II from the Whitehorse shipyards to her current location next to the river at the far end of town. Over eight tons of Palmolive Princess Snow Flake soap lubricated the steel cradle and wooden skids on which she moved. It took 5 weeks to complete the move! Now restored to her original 1937 appearance, the S.S. Klondike was designated a National Historic Site in 1967.

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Did you know 2017 also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

On the west side of Newfoundland's Great Northern Peninsula, you’ll find the crossroads of 6000 years of human history at Port au Choix National Historic Site. Discover one of North America’s most fascinating archaeological finds amid a rugged coastline of unique limestone barrens, forests and bays. Visit ancient burial sites, settlements and view original artifacts, from slate spears to harpoons.

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Did you know 2017 also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

During the mid-16th century, large numbers of right and bowhead whales drew whalers from the Basque region of Spain and France to the Strait of Belle Isle, where they established a major whaling port at Red Bay. For some 70 years, Basque whalers made the dangerous, month-long journey across the Atlantic to hunt whales and produce the oil that lit the lamps of Europe. See original Basque artifacts, remains, and restored chalupa at Red Bay National Historic Site in Newfoundland. 

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Did you know 2017 also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

We’re celebrating #InuvialuitDay! We’re proud to cooperatively manage the beautiful Tuktut Nogait NP with the Inuvialuit. The landscape and wildlife of the 18,890 sq km national park is seen by those privileged few willing to travel 170 kilometres north of the Arctic Circle. The landscape features rolling hills, three major rivers, steep canyons, waterfalls, rare Bluenose west caribou and the continent’s fiercest predators. 

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Stay tuned!

Roughly 30 kilometres southeast of Montréal, Fort Chambly National Historic Site rises proudly at the foot of the Richelieu River rapids. Built in 1711 to defend the colony, this stone fortification was preceded by three wooden forts. The fort has preserved the main elements of its original architecture so that you truly feel like you’re walking in the steps of a French infantryman from the 18th century.

To celebrate #Canada150, we're featuring ALL of our 200+ places across our social media accounts. Did you know 2017 also marks the centennial of national historic sites? Stay tuned!

caption_original:
#ScamAlert: The CRA scam is back in full force.

Beware of scammers impersonating the Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) and claiming that you owe the government back taxes. These scammers “spoof” phone numbers to make it look like the call is from the CRA. 

If you receive a call, ask for the caller’s name, phone number and office location so that you can validate their identity BEFORE you give any personal information. Contact the CRA at 1-800-959-8281 to verify that the caller is legit.

Be vigilant when disclosing personal and financial information over the phone or by email. Here are some tips to tell if it’s really the CRA calling you: http://ow.ly/aaOV301UMld

caption_original: !Here’s Lynne, a biologist with the Canadian Wildlife Service, admiring this Weidemeyer’s while collecting genetic samples to help conserve the species. The Weidemeyer’s Admiral is a large butterfly that is only known in Canada from a small geographic area of southeastern Alberta. The species is listed as Special Concern under Canada’s Species at Risk Act, and little is known about the Canadian population. Cool fact: males of the species are territorial – they patrol and defend an area from all intruders.....

caption_original: Did you know that endangered species conservation is sometimes complex and multi-national? This endangered burrowing owl was fitted with a satellite transmitter near her nest in Alberta in . The solar-powered transmitter allows scientists with the Canadian Wildlife Service and project collaborators to track her movements wherever she goes. After leaving her burrow in Alberta this bird flew over ,500km to winter in Central Mexico. In spring she returned to Alberta and nested less than km from where she was first captured. She was recently sighted by biologists in Mexico in the same wintering site as the year before, and we are hoping she makes a safe and successful return to Canada to raise the next generation of owls. 🦉....

caption_original:
Fact or fiction? A tree is a safe hiding place from lightning. When thunder roars GO, INDOORS! 

Fiction: No, in fact standing under a tree is one of the most dangerous places to be during a thunderstorm. Lightning can strike a tree and the current can travel down the trunk and exit two ways: it can side flash from mid-trunk and jump out and hit you. Or, the lightning can flow out through the roots and you can be hit by ground current. If you are in a forested area during a storm, stay on the trail, not near a tree, and keep everyone a few metres apart from each other. http://ow.ly/hl2N30cCX9D
caption_cleaned: Fact or fiction? A tree is a safe hiding place from lightning. When thunder roars GO, INDOORS! Fiction: No, in fact standing under a tree is one of the most dangerous places to be during a thunderstorm. Lightning can strike a tree and the current can travel down the trunk and exit two ways: it can side flash from mid-trunk and jump out and hit you. Or, the lightning can flow out through the roots and you can be hit by ground current. If you are in a forested area during a storm, stay on the trail, not near a tree, and keep everyone a few metres apart from each other. 9D

caption_original:
Our potato genebank stores almost 180 potato varieties. These come from a wide range of countries beyond just Canada. From Ireland to Peru, there's a large amount of diversity in the samples we keep. This is a part of our commitment to global food security - the preservation of the global food supply. 

As our scientist Dr. Benoit Bizimungu explains, "There are many potato varieties that aren’t grown today with traits that are of current or future interest to researchers and educators. Preserving these varieties ensures valuable attributes, and even those with known susceptibility to certain diseases, are kept for the development of future, better varieties." ow.ly/I2Ru30ck05q

caption_original:
Pointe-au-Père National Wildlife Area is one of the best shorebird-watching sites in Quebec. In the spring, flocks of Least Sandpipers congregate at the site, while Great Blue Heron feed in the marshes in the company of Black-crowned Night-herons and large communities of Brants. 

In the summer, American Black Ducks, Mallards, Northern Pintails and Green-winged Teals raise their young and feed on the plentiful invertebrates in the brackish ponds. During the fall migration, Red-throated Loon and Common Loon, and large numbers of Canada Geese, are observed. Large communities of Sanderlings and Semipalmated Sandpipers also use the area, along with the White-rumped Sandpiper. http://ow.ly/plvi30cG7YS #BirdYear #Canada150

caption_original:
The Government of Canada today announced $333 million in federal funding for the Finch West Light Rail Transit Project.
The project will include the design and construction of 11 kilometers of light rail transit line along Finch Avenue West. The line will run between Humber College and the new Finch West Subway Station on the Toronto-York Spadina subway extension. 
The project will result in faster commutes over the current bus system, and new economic growth and employment opportunities. It will also improve access to public transit, reduce greenhouse gas emissions, and improve mobility for commuters in the area. http://infc.gc.ca/1927
caption_cleaned: The Government of Canada today announced $333 million in federal funding for the Finch West Light Rail Transit Project. The project will include the design and construction of kilometers of light rail transit line along Finch Avenue West. The line will run between Humber College and the new Finch West Subway Station on the Toronto-York Spadina subway extension. The project will result in faster commutes over the current bus system, and new economic growth and employment opportunities. It will also improve access to public transit, reduce greenhouse gas emissions, and improve mobility for commuters in the area.

caption_original:
We are excited to share some pics of another important milestone for the new Champlain Bridge - the installation of the first pier cap!

But what’s a pier cap? Well, it is the massive, W-shaped steel structure that the bridge’s three traffic corridors will rest on. 

As you can imagine, installation of this 261-ton giant is quite a feat. To lift each half-cap piece, two cranes are used to position it in the air vertically, and precisely set it onto the legs so that a second piece can be joined to it in exactly the same way.

The connection in the centre needs to be made with pinpoint accuracy to ensure the pier cap is solid and able to fully carry out its function.
http://ow.ly/HzpN30cMQ0V
It was a sight to behold, but don’t worry if you missed it! A total of 36 pier caps will be put in place over the coming months.
caption_cleaned: We are excited to share some pics of another important milestone for the new Champlain Bridge - the installation of the first pier cap! But what’s a pier cap? Well, it is the massive, W-shaped steel structure that the bridge’s three traffic corridors will rest on. As you can imagine, installation of this -ton giant is quite a feat. To lift each half-cap piece, two cranes are used to position it in the air vertically, and precisely set it onto the legs so that a second piece can be joined to it in exactly the same way. The connection in the centre needs to be made with pinpoint accuracy to ensure the pier cap is solid and able to fully carry out its function. It was a sight to behold, but don’t worry if you missed it! A total of pier caps will be put in place over the coming months.

caption_original:
"Travel on a plane, train, bus, or ferry is not just a convenience – it's an essential part of modern life.  We should move as close as possible to universal accessibility, with individual accommodation as the failsafe, not the default.  We should design for accessibility, build for accessibility, and train staff for accessibility. One in seven Canadians has a disability and this proportion is rising as the population ages, so this is both an ethical and a business imperative."

Scott Streiner speaks to the Accessibility Advisory Council on making Canada's national transportation system the most accessible in the world - from principles to practice. #a11y 

http://ow.ly/8HZG30cEWi0

caption_original:
Biology students from École St. Patrick High School in Yellowknife, NWT, learned about environmental monitoring from biologists working on the Giant Mine Remediation Project. Students received hands-on experience with the Giant Mine Remediation Project team on how environmental monitoring helps ensure the safety, health and protection of Northerners and the environment. 

While students took samples of invertebrates (small bugs), water, sediment, and small fish for live release from the Yellowknife River, project team members explained how the different types of sampling help evaluate the health of an ecosystem.  The Project team was excited to show students a real-life application of the science they are learning in the classroom.
